## LLM Integration Notes

- llama.cpp is exposed as an OpenAI-compatible HTTP server.
- All LLM calls go through a single adapter at `backend/app/agents/base_agent.py`.
- Never call the LLM server directly from services or route handlers — always go through an agent class.
- The base agent handles retries, token counting, and logging to `agent_runs` table.
- Default model: `qwen3-27b` (set in `.env` as `DEFAULT_MODEL`).
- Qwen3 performs best with explicit role definitions, step-by-step reasoning instructions, and JSON output schemas in prompts. Structure all agent prompts accordingly.

## CLI Script Rules
- Every script in backend/scripts/ MUST include the following path bootstrap
  as the first code after the module docstring, before any app imports:

  import sys
  from pathlib import Path
  sys.path.insert(0, str(Path(__file__).resolve().parents[2]))

- This ensures scripts run correctly from any working directory.
- pyproject.toml with `pip install -e .` is the permanent fix but the
  bootstrap must still be present as a fallback.

  ## Settings Access Rule
Always access settings fields using lowercase snake_case attribute names matching
the field definitions in backend/app/config.py. Never use UPPER_CASE env var names
directly on the settings object.
  Correct:   settings.database_url
  Incorrect: settings.DATABASE_URL

  ## Session Usage Rule
Scripts and demos must never construct their own engine or sessionmaker.
Always import and use AsyncSessionLocal from backend.app.db.session:

  from backend.app.db.session import AsyncSessionLocal
  async with AsyncSessionLocal() as db:
      ...